        "faq": {
            "sectionTitle": "❓ Frequently Asked Questions",
            "items": [
                {
                    "question": "Is it bad to charge to 100% every night?",
                    "answer": "Not ideal, but not catastrophic. Li-Ion batteries suffer the most chemical stress at extremes — below 10% and above 90%. Daily charging to 100% slightly accelerates degradation, but less than a single DC Fast Charging session at high temperatures.\n\n💡 Golden rule: keep between 20%-80% for daily use. Charge to 100% only before long trips."
                },
                {
                    "question": "What do I do if the report shows RED (High Risk)?",
                    "answer": "A RED score doesn't automatically mean 'don't buy'. It means 'don't buy without a second opinion'.\n\n🔍 We recommend:\n1. Request a Level 2 Diagnosis (The Surgeon) for live battery data.\n2. If confirmed SoH is below 75%, request a physical inspection at an authorized service center.\n3. Use the report as a negotiation tool — a SoH of 78% vs. 92% can make a difference of thousands of EUR in price."
                },
                {
                    "question": "How accurate is the AI Risk Score?",
                    "answer": "Our score doesn't tell you 'the battery has exactly 87.3% health'. That would be a lie without live data. What our AI does is probabilistic modeling — it analyzes:\n\n• VIN history (accidents, market of origin, recalls)\n• Statistical patterns of the specific model (average NMC vs LFP degradation)\n• Risk indicators (frequent owner changes, imports from unreliable markets)\n\nIt's a risk score, not a live reading. For real SoH, you need Level 2 (The Surgeon)."
                },
                {
                    "question": "Can I send the report to the seller?",
                    "answer": "Yes! Every VoltCheck report can be shared directly via WhatsApp or Email with a single tap. The report includes a secure link valid for the report's lifetime (30 days Level 1 / 365 days Level 2). The seller can view the full report without a VoltCheck account."
                }
            ]
        },
